      <hedline>
        <hl1>Ratify the Sea Treaty</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Howard S Schiffman letter urges US to ratify the 1982 United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>President Clinton deserves credit for using his executive authority to help protect our precious coastlines (news article, May 27). On a deeper level, the United States can show significant leadership by finally ratifying the 1982 United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>President Clinton deserves credit for using his executive authority to help protect our precious coastlines (news article, May 27). On a deeper level, the United States can show significant leadership by finally ratifying the 1982 United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea.</p>
        <p>The law of the sea treaty, already in effect with 133 members, includes many provisions relating to a variety of maritime interests, including shipping, defense and maritime safety,  and marine environmental protection.</p>
        <p>In 1994 a separate agreement addressing the United States' concerns over the deep sea-bed provisions failed to produce our ratification. Presently, only partisan politics in the Senate impedes membership.</p>
        <p>HOWARD S. SCHIFFMAN  Brooklyn, May 27, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is an international lawyer.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
